The HD 97658 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 97658 is a star with 0.89 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.74 times its radius. It is located NaN light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 6 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 97658 is known to have undefined exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 97658 system


HD 97658 b

HD 97658 b was discovered by the undefined observatory using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.08 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 97658 b is 9.54 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 97658 b is 2.354 that of Earth. At 9.54 Earth masses, HD 97658 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
